				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Aggro Management<a name="46322"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jun 16 04 9:54 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>My experience with PC groups is that not much in the way of good group management is practiced.
<br />

<br />
In a typical group, the warrior would pop his aggro on the first inc target (may stick an arrow in in too), switch to the next target (on multiple pull) and fight till he had decent aggro (10% damage done by him), if there is a third, swap to it and pop the renewed disk while everyone else waits then wades in on assist. (or someone root parks or off tanks/mezzes, etc.) You can tell if he's popping his disc, it looks like a spell has landed on and hurt the mob.
<br />

<br />
I'd guess it was just a murder fest...when you have 3 or more melees beating on the same mob (especially if the warrior is not popping his disc) taunt is pretty much usless. A successful taunt just gives the taunter hate +1 over everyone else and that lasts maybe a 1/4 second?
<br />

<br />
Everyone at that level is spamming the taunt key for skillups which means there will ususually be some kind of delay before they can try it again.
<br />

<br />
It gets better.  In fact, there are huge threads in here about how to GRAB AGGRO when you want it. The general concensus is the bard is poor at it, and you have to successfully use several techniques (and get group cooperation) to be even moderately successful. A bard taunt song usually apears in 'wish list' threads.
<br />

<br />
</span></td>
